Census

Last update: 2024/8/2 08:32 -0400

The census is the official record of the structure of the OpenJDK Community. It lists the active Groups, Projects, and Contributors and the relationships between them. The census was initially constructed per the transition plan defined in the ratified Bylaws; details are available below.

To nominate an existing Contributor to a new role, or to propose a new Group or Project, please see the advice and instructions for Groups and Projects.

To request a change or correction to the census, please contact the registrar.

Colophon

The census was initially constructed on 30 August 2011 from the OpenJDK web archives, e-mail archives, and Mercurial repository histories as follows:

  • The initial set of Groups under the new Bylaws was the then-current set of Groups, with their existing Group Members. Group Leads were appointed from the existing Group Moderators when possible; otherwise, a suitable candidate was identified.

  • The new OpenJDK Members Group was created to include those Contributors previously voted into Group Membership. Each such Membership will expire on the anniversary of the initial registration of that Member in the OpenJDK Community database. Members will receive automatic notification, in advance, of Membership expiration.

  • The initial set of Projects under the new Bylaws was the then-current set of Projects. Project Leads were appointed from the existing Project Moderators when possible; otherwise, a suitable candidate was identified.

  • If you created at least one Mercurial changeset for a Project then you were considered an Author for that Project.

  • If you directly pushed one or more changegroups into a Project's Mercurial repositories then you were considered a Committer.

  • Some Projects require formal change review (hsx, jdk6, jdk7, jdk7u, and jdk8). If you pushed at least 32 changegroups into such a Project's Mercurial repositories, or if you were otherwise well-known to be a serious and regular Committer, then you were considered a Reviewer.

  • Most Projects don't require formal change review, and therefore they don't have any Reviewers.

  • If you were an Author, Committer, or Reviewer for the jdk7 Project then you were given the same role for the jdk6, jdk7u, and jdk8 Projects.

  • Projects for which no Sponsoring Group could be identified were, as a temporary measure, sponsored by the Governing Board.

  • In all cases, additional human judgement was applied in order to correct obvious oversights.

Some Groups and Projects have been idle for a long time. The Governing Board will eventually review all Groups and Projects and dissolve those that are inactive.
